  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I take input from STDIN in Python?",
  "response": "In Python, you can take input from `STDIN` (standard input) using the `input()` function. The `input()` function reads a line of text from the user and returns it as a string. Here\u2019s a basic example:\n\n### Example 1: Reading a Single Input\n```python\n# Prompt the user for input\nuser_input = input(\"Enter something: \")\n\n# Display the input\nprint(\"You entered:\", user_input)\n```\n\n### Example 2: Reading Multiple Inputs\nIf you want to read multiple inputs, you can call `input()` multiple times or split the input string as needed.\n\n```python\n# Reading multiple inputs\nname = input(\"Enter your name: \")\nage = input(\"Enter your age: \")\n\n# Display the inputs\nprint(f\"Name: {name}, Age: {age}\")\n```\n\n### Example 3: Converting Input to a Different Type\nThe `input()` function returns a string, so if you need a different data type (e.g., integer, float), you\u2019ll need to convert it explicitly.\n\n```python\n# Read input as a string and convert to an integer\nnumber = int(input(\"Enter a number: \"))\n\n# Display the result\nprint(f\"Square of {number} is:\", number ** 2)\n```\n\n### Example 4: Reading Multiple Values in One Line\nYou can read multiple values separated by spaces (or another delimiter) using `split()` and convert them as needed.\n\n```python\n# Read two numbers separated by a space\nx, y = map(int, input(\"Enter two numbers (separated by space): \").split())\n\n# Display the sum\nprint(f\"Sum of {x} and {y} is:\", x + y)\n```\n\n### Example 5: Using `sys.stdin` for Advanced Input Handling\nFor more advanced use cases (e.g., reading from a file or handling large inputs), you can use the `sys.stdin` object.\n\n```python\nimport sys\n\n# Read all lines from STDIN\nfor line in sys.stdin:\n    print(\"Received:\", line.strip())\n```\n\n### Notes:\n1. `input()` automatically removes the trailing newline character from the input.\n2. Use `strip()` to remove leading and trailing whitespace if needed.\n3. Always validate and handle errors when converting user input to other data types.\n\nThis should cover most of your needs for taking input from `STDIN` in Python!",
